@page "/methodology"

<PageTitle>Methodology - Election Simulator</PageTitle>

<div class="methodology">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>

    <section>
        <h2>Overview</h2>
        <p>
            This simulator projects Canadian federal election results riding-by-riding using
            <strong>Monte Carlo simulation</strong> with an <strong>additive swing</strong> model.
            It runs 10,000 simulated elections, each with randomly generated polling errors drawn from
            heavy-tailed <strong>Student-t distributions</strong> with correlated inter-party noise,
            to produce probabilistic seat projections with confidence intervals.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Swing Model</h2>
        <p>
            The model starts with a baseline election result (e.g., 2025 or 2021) and adjusts each
            riding's vote shares based on how polls have shifted in that riding's region since the baseline.
        </p>
        <p>For each party in each region, an <strong>additive delta</strong> is computed:</p>
        <div class="formula">
            delta = current regional poll &minus; baseline regional average
        </div>
        <p>
            Each riding's baseline vote shares are then shifted by the delta for their region,
            clamped to zero, and renormalized so all parties sum to 100%. This preserves local variation
            while applying regional trends.
        </p>

        <h3>Why Additive Swing?</h3>
        <p>
            Validation across 4 election transitions showed additive swing has 5.6% lower projection
            RMSE than the proportional (ratio-based) alternative. An alpha sweep confirmed that pure additive
            swing minimizes average Brier score, with monotonic improvement from proportional to additive.
            The model supports blending between the two approaches via the <code>SwingBlendAlpha</code>
            parameter (0.0 = pure additive, 1.0 = pure proportional), but defaults to pure additive.
        </p>

        <h3>Missing Ridings</h3>
        <p>
            Due to the 2021&ndash;2025 redistribution, roughly 30 Ontario ridings (and some others) have no
            baseline election data. For these ridings, the model falls back to using the regional polling
            averages directly as projected vote shares.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>By-Elections</h2>
        <p>
            Between general elections, the composition of the House of Commons changes through
            <strong>by-elections</strong> (special elections to fill vacancies), <strong>floor crossings</strong>
            (MPs switching party), and <strong>vacancies</strong> (resignations, deaths, appointments).
            The simulator tracks these post-election events and integrates them in two ways.
        </p>

        <h3>Parliamentary State</h3>
        <p>
            Post-election events are replayed chronologically on top of the baseline general election results
            to derive the current state of each riding. This determines who the current MP is and which party
            holds each seat. The riding detail view shows the full event history for each riding since the
            last general election.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>A <strong>by-election</strong> updates the seat holder to the by-election winner and supersedes any prior floor crossing.</li>
            <li>A <strong>floor crossing</strong> changes the party holding the seat without an election.</li>
            <li>A <strong>vacancy</strong> leaves the seat unoccupied until a by-election is held.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Baseline Blending</h3>
        <p>
            For ridings where a by-election has been held, the simulator blends the by-election results
            into the general election baseline <em>before</em> computing swing projections. The blended
            vote shares for each party are:
        </p>
        <div class="formula">
            effective share = (1 &minus; w) &times; general election share + w &times; by-election share
        </div>
        <p>
            where <strong>w = 0.3</strong> (30%) by default. Shares are renormalized to sum to 100% after blending.
            Ridings without by-elections are unaffected.
        </p>
        <p>
            The moderate blend weight reflects the fact that by-elections carry more recent local signal
            than the last general election, but also have different dynamics&mdash;lower turnout, no government
            formation at stake, and potential for protest voting&mdash;that make them imperfect predictors of
            general election behaviour. By-election data goes back to the 2008 election and is manually curated.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Noise Model</h2>
        <p>
            Polls are imperfect, so the simulator models uncertainty at three hierarchical levels.
            Noise is drawn from <strong>Student-t distributions</strong> (degrees of freedom = 5) rather
            than Gaussian to capture heavy-tailed election surprises&mdash;empirical analysis of residuals
            across 5 election transitions showed significant excess kurtosis that normal distributions
            cannot represent.
        </p>
        <p>
            A scale factor of <code>&radic;((df&minus;2)/df)</code> &asymp; 0.775 is applied so the
            effective standard deviation matches the configured sigma values despite the heavier tails.
        </p>

        <h3>Three Levels of Noise</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>National noise</strong> (per-party sigma, see below):
                One draw per party, shared across all ridings. Captures systematic polling bias&mdash;e.g.,
                polls overestimate the Liberals nationwide.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Regional noise</strong> (base &sigma; = 2.6%, scaled by region):
                One draw per party per region. Captures region-specific polling errors beyond the national trend.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Riding noise</strong> (base &sigma; = 6.5%, scaled by region):
                One draw per party per riding. Captures local-level randomness, candidate effects, and other
                riding-specific factors.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            In each simulation, errors from all three levels are summed and added to the projected
            vote shares. Negative values are clamped to zero, and shares are renormalized per riding.
            The winner of each riding is the party with the highest adjusted vote share (first-past-the-post).
        </p>

        <h3>Correlated Party Noise</h3>
        <p>
            Party noise is not drawn independently. Instead, the simulator uses <strong>Cholesky-decomposed
            correlation matrices</strong> so that when one party receives a positive shock, competing parties
            tend to receive negative shocks&mdash;reflecting the zero-sum nature of vote share competition.
        </p>
        <p>
            The 6&times;6 inter-party correlation matrix was estimated from demeaned residuals across
            5 election transitions (2008&ndash;2025), using 1,431 riding observations. Key correlations include:
        </p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Party Pair</th>
                    <th>Correlation</th>
                    <th>Interpretation</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>LPC &ndash; BQ</td><td>&minus;0.83</td><td>Strong competition in Quebec</td></tr>
                <tr><td>LPC &ndash; PPC</td><td>&minus;0.93</td><td>Strong inverse relationship</td></tr>
                <tr><td>LPC &ndash; NDP</td><td>&minus;0.58</td><td>Left-of-center competition</td></tr>
                <tr><td>NDP &ndash; PPC</td><td>+0.61</td><td>Both gain when LPC declines</td></tr>
                <tr><td>BQ &ndash; PPC</td><td>+0.82</td><td>Both gain when LPC declines</td></tr>
                <tr><td>LPC &ndash; CPC</td><td>&minus;0.18</td><td>Mild direct competition</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Parameters</h2>

        <h3>Default Configuration</h3>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Parameter</th>
                    <th>Default</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>Simulations</td><td>10,000</td><td>Number of Monte Carlo iterations</td></tr>
                <tr><td>National &sigma;</td><td>6.0%</td><td>Fallback national noise (when no per-party value)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Regional &sigma;</td><td>2.6%</td><td>Regional noise base (before per-region scaling)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Riding &sigma;</td><td>6.5%</td><td>Riding noise base (before per-region scaling)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Degrees of Freedom</td><td>5</td><td>Student-t df (higher = closer to Gaussian)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Swing Blend</td><td>0.0</td><td>Pure additive swing</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Correlated Noise</td><td>On</td><td>Cholesky-based inter-party correlations</td></tr>
                <tr><td>By-Election Blend</td><td>30%</td><td>Weight given to by-election results in baseline</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Per-Party National Sigma</h3>
        <p>
            Each party has its own national-level sigma, derived from empirical residuals across 4 election
            transitions. Parties with more volatile historical results receive larger noise.
        </p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Party</th>
                    <th>National &sigma;</th>
                    <th>Rationale</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>LPC</td><td>12.0%</td><td>Highest volatility&mdash;large swings in 2015 and 2025</td></tr>
                <tr><td>CPC</td><td>8.0%</td><td>Second most volatile, consistent across transitions</td></tr>
                <tr><td>GPC</td><td>7.0%</td><td>High relative to vote share</td></tr>
                <tr><td>NDP</td><td>6.0%</td><td>Moderate volatility</td></tr>
                <tr><td>BQ</td><td>4.0%</td><td>Most stable&mdash;concentrated in Quebec</td></tr>
                <tr><td>PPC</td><td>3.0%</td><td>Low absolute volatility; only existed since 2019</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Per-Region Sigma Multipliers</h3>
        <p>
            Both regional and riding sigma are scaled by a per-region multiplier to account for
            geographic volatility differences. Multipliers were derived from empirical residual
            standard deviation ratios across 4 election transitions.
        </p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Region</th>
                    <th>Multiplier</th>
                    <th>Effective Regional &sigma;</th>
                    <th>Effective Riding &sigma;</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>Alberta</td><td>1.41</td><td>3.7%</td><td>9.2%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Quebec</td><td>1.22</td><td>3.2%</td><td>7.9%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>British Columbia</td><td>1.06</td><td>2.8%</td><td>6.9%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Prairies</td><td>0.85</td><td>2.2%</td><td>5.5%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Ontario</td><td>0.81</td><td>2.1%</td><td>5.3%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Atlantic</td><td>0.43</td><td>1.1%</td><td>2.8%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>North</td><td>0.50</td><td>1.3%</td><td>3.3%</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="note">
            The North multiplier uses a floor of 0.50 rather than the raw ratio (0.20) because the
            empirical estimate is unreliable with only 3 ridings.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Demographic Prior (Optional)</h2>
        <p>
            When enabled, the simulator blends swing-projected vote shares with a census-based
            demographic prior before the Monte Carlo noise stage. This uses <strong>ridge regression</strong>
            fitted on historical election results paired with 9 census variables from the 2021 Census
            (retabulated to the 2023 Representation Order):
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Median household income</li>
            <li>University education rate (Bachelor's+)</li>
            <li>Visible minority percentage</li>
            <li>Immigrant percentage</li>
            <li>Francophone percentage</li>
            <li>Population density (log-transformed)</li>
            <li>Median age</li>
            <li>Indigenous identity percentage</li>
            <li>Homeownership rate</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Ridings with no historical baseline data (due to redistribution) receive a higher blend weight,
            giving the demographic model more influence where swing projections are unavailable.
            This feature is off by default.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Interpreting Results</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>The <strong>mean seats</strong> is the average across all 10,000 simulations.</li>
            <li>The <strong>50% confidence interval</strong> (dark bar) represents the 25th to 75th percentile range.</li>
            <li>The <strong>90% confidence interval</strong> (light bar) represents the 5th to 95th percentile range.</li>
            <li><strong>Majority probability</strong> is the fraction of simulations where a party wins 172+ seats (out of 343).</li>
            <li><strong>Minority probability</strong> is the fraction of simulations where a party leads in seats but with fewer than 172.</li>
            <li><strong>Riding win probability</strong> is the fraction of simulations where a party wins that specific riding.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Data Sources</h2>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Source</th>
                    <th>Data</th>
                    <th>Coverage</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Elections Canada</strong></td>
                    <td>Official riding-level results</td>
                    <td>2008, 2011, 2015, 2019, 2021, 2025</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>338Canada</strong></td>
                    <td>Riding-level polling projections</td>
                    <td>Current cycle</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>CBC Poll Tracker</strong></td>
                    <td>Aggregate polling by region</td>
                    <td>Current cycle</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Statistics Canada</strong></td>
                    <td>2021 Census demographics (343 FEDs, 2023 RO)</td>
                    <td>9 demographic variables</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>
            Historical election results are mapped to the current 343-riding boundaries (2023 Representation
            Order). Elections with 338 ridings (2015&ndash;2021) map to ~279 current ridings; elections with
            308 ridings (2008&ndash;2011) map to ~251. Where multiple old ridings map to one new riding,
            vote shares are averaged weighted by total votes.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Validation</h2>
        <p>
            The model is validated using <strong>hindcasting</strong>: predicting a known election from the
            immediately prior election's results (used as both the baseline and the "polling" input).
            This tests how well the swing model and noise calibration perform on real historical shifts.
        </p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Hindcast</th>
                    <th>Riding Accuracy</th>
                    <th>Brier Score</th>
                    <th>CI Coverage (P5&ndash;P95)</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr><td>2025 from 2021</td><td>77.0%</td><td>0.375</td><td>85.4%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>2021 from 2019</td><td>93.2%</td><td>0.167</td><td>99.6%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>2019 from 2015</td><td>87.1%</td><td>0.219</td><td>99.0%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>2015 from 2011</td><td>59.5%</td><td>0.573</td><td>82.4%</td></tr>
                <tr><td>2011 from 2008</td><td>90.4%</td><td>0.178</td><td>98.7%</td></tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
        <p class="note">
            Brier score measures prediction accuracy (lower is better; random guessing &asymp; 0.75 for
            a multi-party system). CI coverage is the fraction of actual riding-level vote shares falling
            within the model's 5th&ndash;95th percentile interval (target: 90%).
        </p>
        <p>
            The 2015-from-2011 hindcast is the hardest&mdash;the 2015 election saw the largest swing in
            modern Canadian history (LPC surge from 3rd place to a majority, NDP collapse). The
            2021-from-2019 hindcast is easiest, as the 2019&ndash;2021 shift was minimal.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Limitations</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>
                The additive swing model assumes uniform movement within regions, which may miss local dynamics
                such as strong incumbent effects or local candidate quality.
            </li>
            <li>
                The combined model sigma (~8&ndash;14% depending on party) is below the full empirical residual
                standard deviation (~23%). The gap is mostly systematic swing model error that cannot be
                captured as random noise without making the model too uncertain.
            </li>
            <li>
                The model is somewhat overconfident at the highest confidence levels&mdash;ridings predicted
                at 90&ndash;100% confidence actually flip about 12% of the time.
            </li>
            <li>
                Student-t noise with df=5 produces kurtosis of 6, partially but not fully addressing the
                empirical excess kurtosis of ~47.
            </li>
            <li>
                Strategic voting, turnout variation, and candidate-specific effects are not explicitly modeled.
            </li>
            <li>
                The BQ is constrained to Quebec ridings; other regional patterns are handled via the
                6-region breakdown (Atlantic, Quebec, Ontario, Prairies, Alberta, British Columbia, North).
            </li>
            <li>
                Ridings created during the 2022 redistribution have no pre-2025 historical data and rely
                on regional polling averages (or the demographic prior if enabled).
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</div>
